'THE HUNTER' TRACKING FUGITIVES
description: ''THE HUNTER,'' which opens today at Loews State I and other theaters, is an exceptionally clumsy, unpleasant action-melodrama based on the real-life adventures of Ralph (Papa) Thorson of Los Angeles, a modern-day bounty hunter. Mr. Thorson makes his living by finding fugitives who have jumped bail. With the exception of the long-gone television series ''Wanted -Dead of Alive,'' which starred Steve McQueen, who also stars here as Mr. Thorson, bounty hunting is an occupation that's seldom been highly regarded in the mythical Old West of movies and television. Deep-down, I assume, we all think of bounty hunting as another form of flesh peddling.

description: TAKE the adventure out of an adventure movie, and what have you got? A lot of hearty he-men, barking commands or insults and offering terse congratulations on a job well done. Anyone who can't figure out what the job is in ''Raise The Titanic!'', incidentally, ought to go see a film that's less demanding. Finding one won't be easy.

'BODYGAURD UNDERDOG'S COURAGE
description: ''MY BODYGUARD'' is a sweet little movie about characters who really seem to be people, and that sort of verisimilitude is rarer than it ought to be nowadays. Though it's no match for a movie like ''Breaking Away,'' it has a similar wry folksiness. And the fact that ''My Bodyguard'' is also set in the Middle West may explain some of its offbeat appeal. When movie teen-agers cannot be counted on to get into New York street fights or Los Angeles rollerskating contests, it becomes imperative that a director and screenwriter find them something else to do.

MISS NEWTON-JOHN IN 'XANADU'
description: I was puzzled by the ads for ''Xanadu,'' because they showed a large likeness of Olivia Newton-John and otherwise gave no idea what sort of movie this could be. Now I understand. ''Xanadu'' doesn't lend itself to quick or easy characterization. Too many different things are going on here, and they don't have much to do with one another. On the other hand, this is still a very muted movie, so ads that created an impression of general frenzy wouldn't do the trick, either. Miss Newton-John really is the film's only clear-cut drawing card.

description: ''Battle Beyond the Stars,'' which opened in neighborhood theaters yesterday, is science fiction inspired by Kurosawa's ''Seven Samurai'' and visited by the spirit of a wiseacre Lewis Carroll. A harmless planet, whose inhabitants appear to have wandered out of a biblical epic, is threatened by a terrifying invader. The planet sends out a volunteer to find mercenaries. He does, and they all return to fight the invader. The invaders die, and so do five of the seven mercenaries. That's the Kurosawa part.

description: WHEN last seen at the fade-out of Hal Needham's ''Smokey and the Bandit'' in 1977, Bandit (Burt Reynolds), his trucker buddy, Snowman (Jerry Reed), and Bandit's friend Frog (Sally Field) had trucked 400 cases of contraband Coors Beer from Texas to Georgia, to win an $80,000 bet and national fame. 'WILLIE AND PHIL' 3 LIVES, SORT OF SHARED
description: IT is 1970 in Greenwich Village. Willie (Michael Ontkean), who is young, Jewish and ambitious, is a high school teacher who wants to be a jazz pianist. Phil (Ray Sharkey), who is young, Italian and ambitious, is a commercial photographer who wants to be a big success. One night, Willie and Phil meet coming out of the Bleecker Street Cinema after having seen ''Jules and Jim.'' Phil, the extrovert, wants Willie, the introvert, to ask him about his recently ended love affair. Willie does, and Phil answers, at length, thus to begin a lifelong friendship. As the film's narrator tells us, Willie and Phil share a sense of humor, a hatred for the Vietnam War and a love for the films of Francois Truffaut.

JUN,'A STORY OF JAPAN TODAY
description: ''JUN'' is the story of a young man who expresses his malaise, his loneliness, and perhaps his general dissatisfaction with contemporary Japanese life by fondling women on subway trains. The debut film of the director, Hiroto Yokayama, ''Jun'' contains a couple of interesting photographic effects and some very muffled emotions. The title character, played by Jun Eto, is about as inexpressive as a character can be, and the film's style is numbingly blank. Halfway between solemnity and pornography, it isn't really anywhere at all.

MOVIE:'THE ADVENTURES OF PICASSO'
description: The Adventures of Picasso'' is billed as ''a lunatic comedy,'' and while it does achieve that feeling on a couple of rare occasions, for the most part it's like a bad dream. This leaden Swedish farce invents a life of slapstick and idiocy for the artist, and parenthetically lambasts everyone from Rembrandt to Toulouse-Lautrec in the process. Ernest Hemingway is seen sitting in a Parisian cafe, wearing a T-shirt that says ''Hemingway'' and knitting mittens. It's remarkable that a film can be so full of fancifulness without developing anything resembling real wit.
